  • Clip for fan wire on the rear of the duct
  • Blower attaches to duct with 2, 18mm long M4 machine screws threaded directly into the plastic

description.text:
I was trying to reduce desk clutter and I wanted a way to hang my iPhone 6 on the wall and still have it charge. I originally designed this with the thought that I would use command strips or double stick tape, i've since done a remix of the original design with a thicker back wall and added two screw holes. The whole design is parametrically designed in Fusion 360 and i've included the Fusion 360 file so you can edit the parameters and make it fit perfectly. It took about three minutes for me to open up the file, change the build parameters to match my iPhone 5s and generate the gcode file.

Once you print this, put the back of the dock against the corner edge of your desk (so the cord cutout is facing away from the desk but is aligned with the sharp edge of the desk) and push down on the sides, with that little bit of flex you should be able to slide the connector in the recess (top to bottom).

description.text:
Hi Guys!

My Mom has been in the hospital for nearly a week now. Recently the hospital changed to a "room service" style food service. So when you want to eat, you have to call 1760 to order your meal, or be awake when they come through to take your order before each meal. The problem is the older phones that the hospital has in each room was designed for the hospital beads in the day. Today's hospital beds are more streamlined and rounded, making it so the phone can't be attached to the bed rail. So they either place it in the bed with her, or place it on a shelf behind the bed. Either way, Mom can't reach the phone.

So the other night I brought a pair if digital calipers and quickly mocked up this adapter. It fits over the rounded bed rail but has a square body to allow the phone to grab it easily. In turn the fastening system of the phone pinches the adapter causing it to pinch the bed rail.

Now hopefully she can order what she wants instead of taking whatever they give her to eat.

  • finish Stellarium plugin to allow slew (goto) commands from within Stellarium, possibly with gcode?

Amazon Basic Nano Speaker Bike Mount

The Amazon Basic Nano speaker is under $15 and works great on a bicycle as it is designed to hang and has a loop which allows you to hang it off the handle bars. The issue with hanging it on the handlebars is that the speaker will be facing left or right. Plus, it will slide down the bars and bump against the steering tube. Custom Builders Tips:

Motors: Keep the kv rating below 2400kv (can still do 54 mph which is great) on the metal diff build for heat purposes as 3500kv was a bit too much, allowing for 80mph on 12t, but super poor efficiency leading to 250F (110C) motor temps. It's not a good thing for the plastic: it warped the NGen center case a fair amount... and that's high temp stuff. Luckily Colorfabb makes another co-poly plastic (HT) that can withstand 100C. Might be a good idea to order some if you don't have it already, and are looking for some fast speed runs ;).

Shocks: I am currently using old Traxxas Slash 4x4 Shocks in the front, so if you dont want to design downstops for them (suspension limiting spacers), then comment below and I'll post them in the list of stls. Front: 83.50mm in the closest mounting hole
Rear: 97.75mm in the furthest mounting hole

-Modified the F-6 and R-8.65 arms for stronger outer hingepin support.

Following a not-even-a-lap-around track run, I managed to break all of the suspension pieces (Petg) on one corner. These part weren't solid parts, but they were around 75-90% infill. So, I'm planning on printing nylon and eventually nylonx to make for a more durable car overall.

comments.text: Its really a matter of testing for how much travel the axles will allow for before theshaft fall out of the out drive cups. So, to design the down stops, you need to measure the length of the shock fully extended and at the point mentioned above. Subtract the needed travel length (or desired length for droop tuning) from the fully extended length and you have the height of the down stops. To make one, draw a cylinder that fits inside the shock's reservoir, with an inner through hole slightly larger than the shock shaft's diameter. The extruded length will be the calculated distance from before.

description.text:
PLEASE READ PRINT SETTINGS AND NOTES

I've seen many box design Tofu Presses on Thingiverse, but not many two-panel vice designs. There are 4 parts to print, two of which should be printed twice.

Construction and operation is as follows:
1: Insert both screws into the base from the bottom. The curve on the screw stand should align with the curvature of the base (These can be glued in place, but should work fine w/o glue as long as pressure is applied to the base when the handles are tightened).
2: Place tofu (or other food item you are trying to flatten) with paper towels underneath and above in the center of the base (Atop grooves).
3: Place Top of press over screw rods by lining the holes up. the flat side of the top should be face up, with the grooves creating a sandwich with the base. (like a George Foreman grill)
4: Place handles over each screw rod and twist to tighten until tofu is compressed
5: Wait about 30 minutes or until water stops draining from tofu (Tighten as necessary to squish out all liquid). Dump excess water in sink, and dispose of paper towels.

MakerBot

No

Infill:

60% or higher for Screw Rods, 30% for handles, 10% for Top and Base

Notes:

This MUST be printed with PLA plastic! ABS is NOT food safe!

Proper arrangement on the build plate in Makerbot Desktop is as follows:
Screw Rods: Horizontal with supports (This will be a pain to clean up, but when printing vertically I noticed a propensity for the rods to snap along the print grain. Horizontal printed rods will take more time, but will be much more durable!)
Base: Ridged side Down, legs pointing UP.
Top: Ridged side UP, flat face on Down on surface.
Handles: Cylinder knob pointing UP, flat side of handle Down on surface.

I recommend printing with 2-3 shells for optimal results.

For a larger Tofu Press, like the one I printed and have shown in the photos, All components may be scaled around +-25% to preference!
If you do this, make sure you scale EVERY component or they will NOT fit together!

To reduce chipping off into food/making plastic food safe

I advise you to sand the Base and Top where the grill lines are with a fine grade sandpaper. Make sure to get into each groove and remove any loose threads of filament that may not have adhered to the component. Afterwards, wash thoroughly with wipes, sponge, ect. to remove ALL plastic powder. Don't eat powdered plastic!

Design:

I 3D modeled all components in Blender, a free 3D design software.

https://www.blender.org/

I have included a video tutorial on how to make a simple screw and handle that will work when printed.

Video Tutorial for designing 3D printable Screws in Blender Video Tutorial for designing 3D printable Handles in Blender

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A very quick and simple proof of concept for a dogtag protector. We used cheap rubber ones before to reduce noise and avoid injuries, but they'd typically become brittle, tear, or cut themselves within weeks. I actually wanted to print these with flexible filament, but since I've only got PLA right now, still gave it a go and the result works rather well.

The STL is designed for a 50x28x0.8mm dogtag. One side is open so you can slide the dogtag in, even if it's PLA.

Make sure to print it upright and with supports, Otherwise Slic3r wouldn't create the top layer for me (open for suggestions). I also used a small brim just to be sure.

There's no cleanup required, but based on the actual dogtag size and your printer's accuracy, you might have to increase the opening a tiny bit (it was a very tight fit for me)..

This is a camera mount for the GEPRC LX5 5" Leopard frame.
The overall angle is 35 degrees (accounts for the natural angle of that frame ~ 25 degrees).

It sits right in between the 2 aluminum braces using the oblong holes in the braces to secure itself. The oblong pods have holes for small zip-ties to secure the VTx to it. I found this frame to be relatively small. I use a TBS Unify Pro HV which can heat up so I designed air intake vents on the mount to keep it cool. I had some interference between Vtx and Rx so I relocated the Unify Pro SMA to the GoPro which was far enough from the Rx (and Rx antennas) to get rid of it.

I recommend TPU and 50% in-fill. Use support for it and have the front of the mount sit flat on the build plate. Supports aren't too difficult to clean up.

Edit: I added a version without the rear VTx antenna mount.

I recommend TPU and 50% in-fill. Use support for it and have the front of the mount sit flat on the build plate. Supports aren't too difficult to clean up.

This is a model to be used for finding final dimensions for a heatsink to be used with the LimeSDR in an Aluminum case available on Ebay.

The heatsink design is done with freecad, and exported as the model for printing. It is undersized in the vertical dimension.

Print the model, then use your board, spacers, and case to determine with a feeler gauge how much larger the actual heatsink should be. There should be enough of a gap left to install silicone transfer pads on top of the three large ICs. I used 2mm thick pads. I also put small pads between the voltage regulators on the bottom of the board, and the bottom of the case.

I used m3 nuts under the board as spacers, and tapped three holes on the heatsink to fasten it to the case with three m3 flathead screws. I also used flathead screws in countersunk holes for the board.

The heatsink is machined out of a solid block of aluminum, and transfers heat to the case.

comments.text: Which kv and prop size did you use for the 1811s?
comments.author: recursion

comments.text:
The original design used to 2900kv motors. I ended up using t-motor MT1306's. Slight modification to the mounting holes, and it works nicely, although considerably more expensive than the Hobbyking 1811's. You should also be able to use RCX 1804 2400kv motors. Inexpensive, more torque due to their pancake design, and seem to be better overall quality than the Hobbyking 1811's.
In all cases I've used 5x3" 2-blade props.
